    "recap_url": "https://www.upstatespartans.com/news/2026/3/13/wylie-waters-three-hit-three-rbi-night-powers-baseball-to-series-and-big-south-opening-win-over-high-point",
    "recap_headline": "University of South Carolina Upstate Athletics",
    "recap_text": "SPARTANBURG, S.C. \u2013\nPoetically, following the battle the two teams fought over the league's regular season crown last season, it's only right that Big South Conference play in 2026 begins with USC Upstate baseball and High Point, as was the case Friday afternoon. Familiar foes, meeting nine times over the past two seasons, the 10\nth\nmeeting since the beginning of the 2024 campaign saw the Spartans rally from an early deficit en route to a 9-7 victory, defeating the Panthers at Cleveland S. Harley Park.\nWhile High Point struck first behind a pair of home runs in the first, Upstate did not flinch, fighting back to tie the game on a two-run shot from senior first baseman\nWylie Waters\nin the second. Despite seeing the Panthers add another tally in the third, the Spartans charged back with a four-spot in the home half, taking the advantage and not looking back.\nUpstate tacked on insurance runs in the fifth, sixth, and eighth innings\u2014allowing it to withstand a three-run ninth inning from the Panthers\u2014leading to the 9-7 victory and a 1-0 record in Big South play.\nWaters, powered by his two-run opposite field blast, led the way with a career-high-tying three hits, adding an RB-I double as he tied his season-best with three RBI. Redshirt sophomore rightfielder\nKenan Bowman\nand fifth-year senior designated hitter\nJohnny Sweeney\neach drove home two runs while Bowman and redshirt sophomore shortstop\nMaloy Heaghney\ncollected two hits apiece.\nBattling back from a pair of first-inning runs against him, junior left-handed pitcher\nChris Torres\nearned the win after turning in 5.0 innings while striking out six. In relief, redshirt freshman right-hander\nJacob Kirby\nturned in 3.1 innings before handing the ball over to freshman righty\nAndrew Kummer\nto slam the door in the ninth for his first career save.\nGame Information\nScore: USC Upstate 9; High Point 7\nRecords: USC Upstate (9-10; 1-0 Big South); High Point (10-8; 0-1 Big South)\nLocation: Cleveland S. Harley Park | Spartanburg, S.C.\nHow It Happened\nT1: Opening the day's scoring, High Point launched a pair of solo home runs in the first. Willie Ponce jumped on the first pitch of the game, sending it to deep right, before Lane Allen launched a 1-1 pitch later in the frame to deep left.\nB2: Tying the game,\nWylie Waters\ndelivered a clutch two-run shot to right-center for the Spartans\u2014their first extra-base hit of the contest.\nT3: Answering the deadlock, the Panthers regained the lead behind a Jake McCarter single to left.\nB3: Sending nine Spartans to the plate in the stanza, Upstate provided its rebuttal in the form of a four-run third.\nJohnny Sweeney\nbroke open the innings scoring, chasing home a pair of leadoff baserunners with a two-run single ripped through the right side. Tacking on, Waters drove home Sweeney with a double to right-center before later scoring on a bases-loaded walk drawn by\nGage Griggs\n.\nT5: Getting a run back, Seojun Oh drove home a run for High Point with a single to left-center.\nB5: Providing an immediate answer, Upstate, taking advantage of three free bases in the frame, pushed across a run on a\nJake Armsey\nwalk with the bases loaded.\nB6: Again, capitalizing with the bases juiced, the Spartans hung another on the board using a\nKenan Bowman\nsac fly.\nB8: Adding a final insurance run, Bowman delivered again for Upstate, dropping a double into shallow rightfield, scoring\nMaloy Heaghney\n.\nT9: Hitting his second long ball of the night, Allen plated three for the Panthers with a shot to left.\nNotable\nTossing the final 0.2 innings for the Spartans Friday evening,\nAndrew Kummer\nearned his first career save. He becomes the fifth different Upstate pitcher to record a save this season, joining\nReece Hemmerling\n,\nJacob Kirby\n,\nCayden Mackey\n, and\nJuan Reyes\n, with each pitcher earning their first career saves this season.\nWith Upstate's victory Friday evening, head coach\nKane Sweeney\ncaptured his 20\nth\ncareer victory in conference play, tying the program record for the fastest head coach to 20 conference wins as Upstate skipper. He and former head coach John Daurity (1986-1991) each reached the mark in their first 25 league contests.\nConnect with the Spartans\nFacebook.com/UpstateAthletics\nTwitter | @UpstateBSB | @UpstateSpartans\nInstagram | @UpstateBSB | @UpstateSpartans\nYouTube.com/UpstateSpartans\nINVEST IN CHAMPIONS\n- Join the Upstate Athletic Fund (UAF) and enjoy enhanced benefits for your support of all USC Upstate programs! Make your gift today,\nclick here\n!"
